The long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance. Magazines require no lubricants and can be easily disassembled without tools for cleaning. SureFire High capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip. The 60-round magazine—slightly thinner than two 30-round magazines clipped together and about the same overall length—fits in most dual magazine pouches, eliminating special carry pouches required for drum magazines.

Features:

- Compatible with all weapons that accept standard STANAG 4179 compliant magazines

- Reliable functioning due to mechanical simplicity and high-quality non-binding coil springs—no lubricants required

- Long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance

- Easily seated in weapon with bolt forward

- May be kept fully loaded for extended periods without spring fatigue

- Only 1.66" thick, less than two 30-round magazines clipped together
60-round magazine is approximately same length as two 30-round magazines clipped together

- 60-round magazine fits in most dual-mag pouches

title: For Sale:  Beretta Stampede Nickel Revolver 5.1/2" 45 Colt (o.b.o.$$/FT?)
postcontent:
I am selling my Beretta Stampede Nickel Revolver 5.1/2" 45 Colt (Model 4528).  I purchased it from Gander Mt. Gun World in Germantown, WI, less than a week ago, for almost $650.  (I'll sell it for $540 o.b.o., now.)  I have all the paperwork and the original box.  I did shoot one box of 50 rounds through this gun and there are absolutely NO problems with this gun.

My problem lies with the salesman that sold it to me, or maybe my own ignorance.  I already have a single-action Ruger .357mag and wanted a more powerful gun.  Money being in short supply, I was thinking of selling my .357 to fund my plans.  Then, the gun salesman told me a .44mag and a .45colt were comparably equal, so I went with the .45, which was cheaper.  I found out [too late] that this is not true, doing my research after the fact.  {Hornady ballistics charts put the .44mag at muzzle speeds of 1150-1550 fps with energy levels of 880-1000 ft/lbs, while the .45colt is at 725-920 fps and energy of 300-460 ft/lbs.}

These comparisons are not a problem for somebody who is looking for a .45 Colt single-action revolver that looks amazing and shoots exactly as it is supposed to.  Anyway, the recoil was less than challenging, for me, and it's not satisfying my ambition to have what 'Dirty Harry' would call, “the most powerful handgun in the world.”  :o)

If all things are legal on your part and you would like to own this beautiful six-gun, it can be yours for $540 o.b.o.  I have cleaned and lubricated it again.  You can't get a gun much newer than this one, and  avoid the paperwork, 48-hour wait, and headache, by buying if from a private party.

Oh, I'd also like to have something like a Springfield .40 XD sub-compact pistol, if you'd be interested in doing a trade.

The following description of this .45 Colt is from Beretta's website (I used the pic from their site of this exact gun):

There’s no gun more quintessentially American than the single-action revolver.
The Beretta Stampede combines the feel and handling qualities of the original “hogleg” with a transfer-bar safety system that makes it safe to carry with all six chambers loaded.

The beauty is in the accurate details.  The fixed front sight is true to the original.
And with the frame dimensions closely matched to the 19th-century originals, the Stampede feels slender and very responsive in the hand.
